        <h1>AuroraCast</h1>

        <h2>Project Goals</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>Provide accurate real-time weather updates</li>
            <li>Show a seven-day weather forecast</li>
            <li>Display Air Quality Index (AQI) information</li>
            <li>Generate weather highlights based on conditions</li>
            <li>Support multiple languages</li>
            <li>Offer a modern and responsive interface</li>
            <li>Enable location-based weather fetching</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Features</h2>
        <h3>Current Weather</h3>
        <p>Displays the current temperature, weather condition, date, and location.</p>

        <h3>Seven-Day Forecast</h3>
        <p>Provides daily temperature updates with weather icons for quick reference.</p>

        <h3>Air Quality Index (AQI)</h3>
        <p>Shows pollutant levels including PM2.5, SO2, NO2, and O3, with an AQI status rating.</p>

        <h2>Technology Stack</h2>
        <h3>Frontend</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>HTML, CSS, JavaScript</li>
            <li>EJS for rendering views</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Backend</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Node.js and Express.js</li>
            <li>Axios for API requests</li>
            <li>dotenv for managing environment variables</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>APIs Used</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>OpenWeatherMap API for weather and AQI data</li>
            <li>Geolocation API for retrieving user location</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Installation and Setup</h2>
        <h3>Step 1: Clone the Repository</h3>
        <pre><code>git clone https://github.com/KasoHodaj/AuroraCast.git</code></pre>

        <h3>Step 2: Install Dependencies</h3>
        <pre><code>npm install</code></pre>

        <h3>Step 3: Set Up Environment Variables</h3>
        <p>Create a <code>.env</code> file in the root directory and add:</p>
        <pre><code>WEATHER_API_KEY=your_openweathermap_api_key</code></pre>

        <h3>Step 4: Start the Server</h3>
        <pre><code>npm start</code></pre>
        <p>Once started, visit <code>http://localhost:3000</code> in your browser.</p>

